list.name: Default Changelist
list.comment: Added support for static functions (properties is TODO) Refactored identifier parsing

task.summary: Default task
Added equality operator Closes #26
Added byte and char support Fixed bug that caused the constructor to not be registered as a function Theoretically added support for Half Closes #29
Removed SingleParserState.py Added necessary additions as threadlocal storage to ParserState.py Moved necessary methods to ParserState.py (Part of an ongoing refactoring process)
Moved function call logic into LLVMGen.py Added optimization that moves allocas to the top of the function in release mode
Added config file support Refactored config layout Refactored main.py to be all about arguments Closes #10
Fixed a race condition that would confuse LLVM
Fixed passing variables to functions
Fixed access control for functions

Added option to use LLVM bitcode files instead of object files Switched to prefer Clang but with GCC fallback Added config validation Added struct access control Fixed config merging use a wrong order
Overall Clang nets around 0.1 seconds in the testing/ test However, LLLVM bitcode produces larger binaries than using object files. Not sure why.

Updates for caching system
Fixed bug in main.py that expected release to always be set Completely removed LLVMFunction.py and instead rely on LLVM's Function and Metadata Added monkey patches to ease the above mentioned change Reworked module compilation system to better support this Removed linking in of modules. Doesn't net any benefit as far as my tests have shown so instead of reworking it the removal was easier

Completely removed any state for functions and structs (LLVMFunction.py and LLVMStruct.py) Moved necessary metadata into LLVM metadata Improved certain operations Fixed bug in ParserState.py causing the function to not be returned
Removed inheritance for now

Implemented basic result cache Implemented dependency and hash tracking in module metadata Moved old cache directory to output Removed duplication checker for now as it was a naive implementation that doesn't bode well with the cache (e.g. functions used in other modules are already declared in there so checking for duplicates would involve some extensive logic)
Changed old base64 encoded names into md5 hashed ones
Added Last Modified Time checking to Cache Improved and refactored caching structure and system Added option 'disable_cache' to disable using the cached files Closes #35

Update
Fixed lots of bugs Refactored some code to be more readable Improved exception handling Improved profiling
Improved worst case scenario when looking up functions and structs
Add parser support for global variables Fix two bugs in CLI args missing --profile and variable declarations not having types inferred
Added support for elif constructs Closes #40
Added support for switch/case statement With default statement And multiple cases per block
Moved platform to platform_support since it apparently conflicts with Python's platform

Implemented access checking
Moved function metadata to module to fix bugs Closes #38
Preliminary support for inheritance

Update
Added const global variables Fixed name mangling bug Fixed type mapping bug Added ability to specify "always imported" modules that will always be added to the current usings. Currently limited to builtin. Fixed bug that could occur if a module only had external functions Added Extension Functions Added "Primitive Boxed Types" via extension functions, right now only int32.rial Fixed bug in parsing access modifier from Metadata Fixed bug that could occur when an argument is a pointer to something else than a struct Fixed bug in StructDeclarationTransformer.py when the FDT would discard a function
Added primitive type casting Fixed bug in type to LLVM type mapper not handling shortcuts Removed usage of Literal to support Python3.7 Moved most print-functions into builtin/print.rial

Update
Moved builtin_types to ParserState.py Changed builtin and std to now require rial: prefix Removed cache file hash checking to speed up worst case (and if file modification doesn't match then it most likely changed) Improved compilation speed when cache is disabled Improved compatibility with Python versions
Added ability to work singlethreaded-ish. This was a giant change that completely overhauled the way the compilation units and scheduling was done. Before when a thread encounters a using statement it would block until that using statement was resolved....Now if theres a sufficient number of modules and none of them could completely be resolved you'd get a deadlock. So now threads pack it all up into compilation_unit.py(s) and start working on other files in a double-list fashion. As a result the in-operation support for resolving uses from function names was removed (it was dumb anyways honestly). There's still a lot to be refactored and improved though, especially in regard to readability.
Profiler now checks if an event was already recorded and will append the time to the first event
Rewrote threading. It congests less but doesn't work with caching right now. It's also unnecessarily more complex

Update
Fixed multithreading issues. In particular the GIL caused a lot of lockstep inbetween the various threads which caused a massive slowdown. Fixed caching. Now structs are also cached and don't throw an exception. Dependencies are also correctly saved and not just the last seen one. Fixed cache invalidation. Previously it was only checked if the module was about to be compiled, not if it actually was already compiled. Improved metadata handling. Moved most of the definition metadata into custom subclasses to avoid the parsing overhead and reduce the clutter in the LLVM IR. This also improved the caching situation. Improved profiling Refactored a bit to improve readability

Allow function declarations and function calls to contain reserved characters if enclosed by @"[name]"
Closes #45
Improved grammar to improve readability of the AST Visitors
Inlined an import to avoid errors for an optional target
Implemented globals for non-constant values Refactored function finding which nets a small performance plus Fixed a bug in default constructor generation mixing up type and name Closes #37
Implemented access modifiers for globals Fixed bugs concerning name mangling for globals Refactored global finding for easier readability
Refactorings Got the ol' tests running again
Alloca function return values to reduce allocation-related code size
Added global variable assignment Improved type handling in variables

Update Added support for globally assigning values to global variable Refactored definition finding to use the same method for functions and variables Removed separate usings and compilation_unit.py. Usings is done via RIALModule.dependencies while compilation units aren't used at all anymore. Removed duplicated code
Fixed an issue causing the common startup script start.rial to self-reference

Implemented likely/unlikely for conditions Closes #52
TODO: Switch and while
Also added first draft of stages for checking algorithms

Fixed a bug that would sometimes occur when a particular thread resumes that depends on global variables from another module, since those global declarations were only handled in the ASTVisitor.py and thus were not waited on

Remodeled Declaration Transformers by combining the StructDeclarationTransformer.py and FunctionDeclarationTransformer.py into one, since the top-down nature of TranformerInterpreter ensures the correct execution hierarchy.

Added unsafe contexts, functions and top level blocks Updated builtin to use the new constructs
External functions are now unsafe Added integer to variable conversion, which is also unsafe.
Fixed bug causing variable assignments trying to load Strings as integers Fixed bug causing hex and binary integers to be converted as base-10 Fixed a few unnecessary indirections in function declarations and calls
Closes #22
Added sizeof operator Added option to completely disable every optimization
Added "primitive" arrays Added better sizeof support Improved grammar
Moved LLVMGen to be a threadlocal variable in ParserState.py

Absolute unit of a commit
- Reworked the entire compiler. - It's single threaded now for better performance (lol fuck python) - Definition finding is better now - Variable handling is better now - There still needs to be some work done for feature parity with the old one which now resides in rial_old - Moved to scoped imports - Redid the standard library and some other grammar related things - Improved code readability by A LOT

String work
- Improved CString and String handling - Improved argument and return type handling in general - Fixed codegen.py get_size function not honoring the context the struct was declared in - Fixed a bug in builtin detection - Fixed a bug in sizeof type matching - Added possibility to specify stdlib imports without prefixing them with 'rial:' - Added deduplication to string literal parsing - Fixed string literal size not being recorded - Fixed DesugarTransformer.py using old Transformer - Fixed implicit parameter being appended to the end of the list of arguments instead of the front - Fixed array parsing for function calls - Changed default optimization level to '1' to improve default performance - Fixed CString (in particular) handling by return and variable assignment rules - Fixed variable detection in RIALVariable.py and added __str__ and __repr__ functions
Simplified instantiation of types and arrays
Added char literals and switched chars to be UInts
Improved type mapping
Added support for static functions (properties is TODO) Refactored identifier parsing
